trick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: perhaps an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name. Compare   Merriman  .","English (Lancashire; of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Old French <i>marmion</i> ‘monkey, brat’."],"variants":[{"name":"Merriman","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marmon","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Gloucestershire):","variant of   Marmion  .","variant of <b>Marriman</b>, an occupational name meaning ‘servant of Mary’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’."]}]},{"name":"3rd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Aird  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Aird","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from either the medieval lordship of The Aird (Inverness) or from Aird Farm near Hurlford, Ayrshire. Both are named from Gaelic <i>àird(e)</i> ‘height, promontory’, or ‘headland’, from the adjective <i>àrd</i> ‘high, lofty’, cognate with Latin <i>arduus</i> ‘steep, difficult’. Compare   Ard  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":62,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Marmion 3rd was born in 1153, in Tamworth Castle, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Marimon Lord Scrivelsby, was 54 and his mother, Melisende de Rethel, was 35. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died on 15 May 1218, in Scrivelsby with Dalderby, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1153–15 May 1218":"1153–15. mai 1218","1153–1218":"1153–1218","1160–1210":"1160–1210","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1179–1210":"1179–1210","1182–1242":"1182–1242","1190–1225":"1190–1225","1100–1181":"1100–1181","1118–1165":"1118–1165","8 September 1181":"8. september 1181","